##Chapter 7: Philosophical Reflections on Existence
This book has taken us on a journey to explore a new view of the universe — one that challenges the idea of "infinity." We have questioned the linear nature of time, re-examined the meaning of stillness, and broken down the layers of reality. Now it is time to bring all these ideas together and ask the core question: in a finite, cyclic universe, what is the meaning of our existence? And how should we live?



7.1　Meaning in a Finite Universe: Creation and Giving
For a long time, we have tied the idea of "meaning" to something infinite. The meaning of life comes from eternal salvation. The meaning of history comes from endless progress. The meaning of truth comes from reaching absolute answers.

But Non-Infinity Theory tells us the universe isn't infinite — it's a finite cycle. Does this make our lives small or meaningless? Actually, it's the opposite.

If the universe is finite and cyclic, then every moment we create, every interaction, every choice becomes precious and unique. Even if patterns repeat, the specific you and this specific now will never happen again in exactly the same way. In a world assumed to be infinite, actions can feel diluted — lost in the endless "next times." But in a finite cycle, every "now" carries a one-time-only importance.

Meaning no longer needs to come from a distant, infinite goal. It can be created, felt, and given in each moment. It doesn't come from something waiting to be discovered — it comes from what we build with our hands and feel with our hearts. In limited time and conditions, we can create unique experiences, deep connections, and personal understanding of the world. That act of creation is the true source of meaning.


The Infinite Trap: A Football Match That Never Ends
To explore meaning further, let us think from the opposite position — what if the universe truly were infinite, and time truly were eternal and one-directional? What would happen then?

In that kind of universe, human meaning could only take one form: infinite expansion — infinite desire, infinite technology, infinite conquest. But can this kind of infinity actually carry meaning?

Imagine a football match. Red team versus blue team — but the rules have been rewritten. Time is infinite: there is no final whistle. Resources are infinite: players can be substituted across generations. If the Earth is destroyed, the match simply moves to another planet and continues.

In this match, even if the red team leads by a thousand goals, does that lead mean anything? No. Because across an infinite timeline, the blue team always has time to equalise, even to overturn the result. Every lead is temporary. Every deficit is non-fatal. When the outcome loses its finality — because time never runs out — the meaning of the match collapses entirely. A game that never ends is not a game. It is endless labour.

Eventually the players — or humans, or any higher intelligence — would discover that to recover meaning, they have only one choice: to cherish each pass as it happens. They would have to pretend the match has an ending, or grant absolute weight to "this one minute" inside the game.

This is the most remarkable meeting point between Non-Infinity Theory and its opposite: regardless of whether the universe is physically finite or infinite, consciousness — in order to experience meaning — must operate within a finite frame. In other words, we do not need to prove the universe is physically finite. We only need to acknowledge that any intelligent being seeking existential meaning must embrace the logic of non-infinity.



7.2　Freedom in a Finite Cycle: Maximize Your Choices
If the universe doesn't run on "infinite copies" but instead on "finite reorganizations," then this actually gives us more freedom and power as individuals. Each cycle isn't a perfect replay — it's a familiar pattern with space for small changes and new ideas.

We often think "freedom" means unlimited options or infinite possibilities. But Non-Infinity Theory reminds us that true freedom comes not from breaking all rules, but from doing the most you can within a structure. Like a chess player — there's only one board and fixed rules, but within those limits, countless strategies and creative moves are possible. That kind of freedom — the power to shape within limits — is the most real and powerful kind we have.

Even if similar life events return in our spiral of experience, how we understand them, what we choose, and how we act is still in our hands. This freedom is not the fantasy of "infinite freedom," but the real ability to shape something different inside limits. Each cycle gives us a chance to choose again, to act differently. We can use past experiences to try new attitudes and actions — and that may change the outcome of the next cycle.


Shattering the Illusion: The Hammer That Returns Us to Now
We are often misled by the shape of the container. We argue about whether the universe — this container — extends infinitely outward like an endless plain, or curves back upon itself like a snake eating its own tail. But this argument, at its core, still places "meaning" in the length of space or the location of an endpoint.

The truth is: whether the container is physically infinite or finitely cyclic, it is only a backdrop. Meaning is not a property of the container. It is an emergence — something that only happens at the point called now.

We must see clearly: Non-Infinity Theory is a hammer, built to shatter the illusion of infinity. Its purpose is not to impose a "finite" framework. Its purpose is to guide the observer back to the present moment. When this hammer shatters the false comfort of "there's always later," the observer's gaze is forced back from that distant, imaginary horizon — and refocused on the ground beneath their feet. We challenge infinity not to embrace finitude, but to embrace what is real.

Meaning does not need eternity to prove itself. Consider the moment Michael Jordan leaps — that absolute flowering of life force does not require "this ball will fly forever" to justify its value. The focus of that moment, the choice of that moment, the will of that moment — all of it reaches completion in the instant it occurs. We must understand: Non-Infinity Theory is the path. The present moment is the destination.

When you release your dependence on infinity, you are no longer a wanderer lost on an endless road. You become a creator, fully present in every frame of the spiral. The shape of the universe no longer troubles you — because in your finite leap, you have already touched a freedom that transcends dimension.

This book begins by deliberately challenging the deeply held belief in "infinity" — guiding readers to question habitual either-or thinking. If at this point a reader is still searching for physics data or mathematical proof to disprove infinity, they may still be caught inside a black-and-white framework. Non-Infinity Theory is not simply "finite theory." It is an inclusive way of observing.

Non-Infinity Theory reminds us that exploring the nature of existence should be about understanding the universe — not merely calculating it. It does not seek to move you from infinite theory into a finite cage. Rather, it proposes that finite and infinite can coexist at the same time. This is like the cube analogy introduced in Section 5.5: your viewpoint may not be able to see every face of the cube at once — but every face exists simultaneously. A finite perspective and an infinite whole are simply different dimensions of the same reality.



7.3　The Humble Explorer: Embracing the Unknown, Thinking Together
When we reach the edge of what we know — and accept that we might never know the full answer — our minds actually become more open and free. This kind of humility is the gateway to deeper wisdom.

Non-Infinity Theory is not a fixed belief system. It is a tool for thinking, a new way to understand the universe and ourselves. It asks us to let go of chasing ultimate truths, and instead embrace uncertainty. From that space, we can create meaning of our own.

This book's journey is coming to an end — but the philosophical questioning never truly ends. That's why I want to offer an invitation: let's argue. Not in the sense of fighting to win, but in the sense of open and honest dialogue. It is about exploring the unknown together, letting ideas meet and grow. If we can all admit that we may never have the final answer, then sharing our views becomes even more important. This is how collective wisdom grows. This is how we, at the edge of knowledge, keep expanding understanding and move closer to truth.

We may never fully solve the mysteries of the universe. We can't see every future. But we can choose how to face this limited reality. We can choose to learn, grow, and create meaning in every cycle. We can let go of our obsession with "infinity," and instead live deeply in the “finite."

In the end, the meaning of existence may lie in this: how we choose to experience and interpret this finite, one-of-a-kind journey.
